425"/><CodeA name="root" value="re:singp"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="asiaz"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Asia</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="re:singp"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="seasiaz"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Southeast Asia</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="re:singp"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Insight</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Getting creative to attract young locals</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Instead of working as a traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) therapist, how about being a rehabilitation technologist instead?</Para><Para>Mr Tan Lip Hong, 41, chief operating officer of TCM centre Kin Teck Tong, is counting on the more modern job description to attract a new, more tech-savvy breed of job applicant.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>"We need to think of creative ways to change the job scope or job title to attract locals," he says.</Para><Para>Rehabilitation technologists are likely to work with advanced medical devices at Kin Teck Tong's clinics to customise treatment plans for patients, for example.</Para><Para>In comparison, work as a TCM therapist typically is seen as involving more manual labour.</Para><Para>However, this role, too, could be expanding thanks to advances in technology.</Para><Para>WOOING RESIDENTS</Para><Para>We need to think of creative ways to change the job scope or job title to attract locals.</Para><Para>MR TAN LIP HONG, 41, chief operating officer of TCM centre Kin Teck Tong.</Para><Para>The company, which has 60 employees, is assessing whether to roll out robotic technology to supplement work by therapists practising tui na, a form of Chinese therapeutic massage.</Para><Para>Such measures are necessary as it is becoming more difficult to hire local workers for the TCM sector, which younger Singaporeans tend to view as a less than glamorous occupation, says Mr Tan.</Para><Para>Even though there is a biomedical sciences and Chinese medicine double degree programme at Nanyang Technological University, there is no guarantee the graduates will join the industry.</Para><Para>To find quality local candidates for therapist or physician roles, the wait can be as long as three to four months, Mr Tan says.</Para><Para>If the vacancy remains unfilled, other employees may be overworked or the company will be unable to serve as many patients as it wants to at its three clinics.</Para><Para>"Business is so competitive, we don't have the luxury of time to wait several months to find someone, so in those cases we have to look at alternatives from overseas," he says.</Para><Para>At the same time, the wait for Employment Pass applications for higher-skilled foreigners to be approved has lengthened, he says.</Para><Para>Top-tier jobs at the company are reserved for locals, who are bilingual and are familiar with the market and regulations, and over 90 per cent of its physicians are Singaporeans or permanent residents, says Mr Tan, adding: "As a homegrown company, we want to have a strong Singaporean core."</Para><Para>Joanna Seow</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Joanna Seow </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">TCM centre Kin Teck Tong's chief operating officer Tan Lip Hong (in blue shirt) with (from far left) receptionists Annie Wong and Winnie Wong; brand operations manager Lydia Liu; therapist Lee Ai Guo; and physicians Yang Ling, Sheryl Teo and Zhang Yao Jia. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

